defaultEIS 39defaultWritten evidence submitted by the defaultMineral Products Association (MPA)default&#xa0;
defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
defaultThe Mineral Products Association (MPA) is the trade association for the aggregates, asphalt, cement, concrete, dimension stone, lime, mortar and silica sand industries. 
defaultWith the recent addition of The British Precast Concrete Federation (BPCF) and the British Association of Reinforcement (BAR), it has a growing membership of 465 companies and is the sectoral voice for mineral products. MPA membership is made up of the vas
defaultt majority of independent SME companies throughout the UK, as well as the 9 major international and global companies. It covers 100% of GB cement production, 90% of aggregates production, 95% of asphalt and ready-mixed concrete production and 70% of precas
defaultt concrete production. Each year the industry supplies £9 billion of materials and services to the £120 billion construction and other sectors. Industry production represents the largest materials flow in the UK economy and is also one of the largest manuf
defaultacturing sectors.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe following answers are valid for the UK industries represented by MPA members, where possible and appropriate:
default&#xa0;
default1.  What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK?default&#xa0;
defaultThe usual means of assessing the econo
defaultmic contribution of industries or sectors is through Gross Value Added (GVA). The main problem with such analyses set out in official statistics is that they tend to understate the overall contribution of extractive industries due to the scope of the stand
defaultard industrial classifications used. For extractive industries this means that sectoral GVA will typically not cover value added or downstream activities.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn 2012 MPA commissioned Capital Economics
default 
defaultto evaluate the economic contribution of the industries 
defaultand companies represented by MPA. This scope covered mineral extraction and processing but also the manufacture of mineral products such as cement, concrete and asphalt and associated activities such as industry transport. Outcomes of the research included
default:
