default2.  How do the UK-based extractive industries support employment a) in the UK and b) for UK citizens overseas?default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere are two distinct elements to this question: direct 
defaultemployment and indirect employment.  The Capital Economics research defined direct employment as those engaged in extraction, the production of mineral products and associated activities and estimated direct employment in 2011 at between 33,000 and 39,000.
default The research also estimated that 37,200 jobs in the industry supply chain were supported by the mineral products industry within the scope of MPA membership. The direct employment of the industry is distributed throughout the UK and is predominantly rural
default based. There are particular concentrations of direct employment in The East Midlands, South West and Yorkshire and Humberside regions of England and in Scotland. Supply chain or indirect employment is also distributed nationally, with significant employme
defaultnt in the North West, East and West Midlands and South East of England.
default&#xa0;
default(b) There is no
default direct knowledge
default of the UK indigenous extractive minerals industries
default’ support for UK citizens overseas
default.
default&#xa0;default3.  Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s defaultposition as a centre for extractive industries e.g. in sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?default&#xa0;
defaultBeing modern industries the UK extractive minerals industries are customers for a huge number of manufactured products, rangi
defaultng from ICT equipment at one end of the scale, to heavy mobile or static plant at the other end
default (Including marine aggregate dredgers at £35 million)
default.  Some of this will be indigenously produced – a classic example might be JCB equipment and plant – but muc
defaulth will not, albeit some plant and equipment will be franchised to UK manufacturers that are owned overseas
default, and
default much of the repair and maintenance work will be carried out by UK operators
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultTraditionally, the UK has been a manufacturer of such plant and eq
defaultuipment, possibly stemming from the fact that much of the high end technical training and education has been done at the Royal School of Mines or its Cornish counterpart, the Camborne School of Mines, and other British Universities, generating a long stand
defaulting relationship with things British!  In the global current market, however, it is doubted whether the UK supporting industries benefit from either traditional empathy or training experience, other than in consultancy work such as law, design, environment
defaultal management, health and safety or general management.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default4.  Has the boom in London-listed extractive companies with businesses overseas over the last two decades resulted in a strengthening in the UK’s competitive position in this sector?default&#xa0;
defaultThis is not s
defaultomething on which MPA can comment directly, as its responsibilities lie solely with UK operations, albeit with an additional interest in European Commission and Parliamentary activities, where they have the potential to influence the way the industries in 
defaultthe UK operate.  In percentage terms the tonnages of UK extracted (non-energy) minerals and downstream products owned by overseas listed companies is about 75%, the remainder (UK owned, but not necessarily listed) being solely involved in UK based operatio
defaultns.  It should be noted in this context that the level of regulation, the high cost of energy and difficulties in establishing reserves with planning consents (replenishing land banks) has the potential to divert future investment in the UK to more profita
defaultble operations overseas, thus endangering the resource security of essential minerals for the UK market.
default&#xa0;
