default&#xa0;default6.  Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector?default Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?default&#xa0;
defaultThe relationship between the extractive minerals industries in the UK and the NGOs has been transformed over the past decade or so, such that the joint work and
default initiatives being carried out in the UK are now signalled as exemplars worldwide.    It is on record, for example, that Natural England, as the English environmental policy advisor to Government, has stated that the MPA members have the ability, with care
defaultfully managed operations and subsequent site restoration, to satisfy 100% of nine out of 11 UK Biodiversity Action Plan targets 
defaulton their owndefault.  Further, NE has said that the UK extractive minerals industries “are uniquely placed…..” to enhance biodiversity in the country and, in tandem with the RSPB and the industries, has created an initiative called “Nature after Minerals”, which has as its b
defaultasis the desire to ensure that extractive operations and restoration make the most beneficial contribution to UK biodiversity over the long term. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere has been a particularly productive relationship developed between the UK’s marine 
defaultaggregate 
defaultdredging i
defaultndustry, regulators, agencies and NGOs which has resulted in a greater understanding of the marine environment.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne factor in the closer relationship between the UK mineral products industry and NGOs was the availability of funding from the UK aggregates 
defaultlevy through the operation of the Aggregates Levy Sustainability Fund (ALSF). The ALSF was set up when the aggregates levy was introduced in 2002 to direct a proportion of levy revenues into initiatives to minimise environmental impacts and support local c
defaultommunity initiatives. Over a number of years about 6% of aggregates levy funding was used for ALSF purposes. Although independent research identified significant benefits and value for money arising from the ALSF, the scheme was scrapped by Government in E
defaultngland in 2011 and the only part of the UK in which the schemes continues is Wales. The marine aggregates ALSF programme was described recently by the body representing industry, regulator, agency and NGO interests as 
default“one of the most substantial investmen
defaultts in UK marine research 
defaultthat has taken place this decade
default”
default and the outputs from this programme have delivered significant added value in supporting the UK Government’s wider objectives for sustainable marine management, particularly the development of mari
defaultne planning.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis very effective mechanism to encourage positive and productive projects and initiatives involving industry, NGOs and other interested parties could be viewed as a template for co-operative work in the extractive se
defaultctor elsewhere in the wo
defaultrld. MP
defaultA believes that the withdrawal of the ALSF in England n 2011 was a short sighted and damaging decision by Government.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe MPA’s Biodiversity and Restoration Awards, to be held in London on 16 October, will amplify these strong relationships and con
defaulttributions developed with NGOs and other organisations.
default&#xa0;default7.  Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas?default&#xa0;
defaultThe experi
defaultence of the MPA members is that the average age of the workforce has increased to the extent that a high percentage of those (directly) employed is now over 50 years old.  The question remains as to whether there is, or has been sufficient backfilling with
default the right numbers and levels of expertise, itself asking a supplementary question about the depth and quality of education and training available, as much as a wider one on the image of the extractive industries and their attractiveness to newer generatio
defaultns!  The requisite skills base is probably in place, but whether is being directed accurately to fulfil the future further demands of the extractive minerals industries is less certain. Further, with the reduction or closure of certain types of extraction 
defaultindustry, notably underground mining, in the UK there are fewer sites where trainees can learn their trade by practical, hands on site training in this country, 
defaultwhich has reduced still further the ability to provide high quality experts in relevant fields.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe mineral products industry is now working closely with the University of Derby to support the establishment and development of the University as a centre of excellence for extractive industry education. 
default&#xa0;
