default&#xa0;
defaultThe EITI requires significant
default reporting and verification of data from extractive industries operating in the UK but we have yet to receive clarity about the implications for UK operators.
default&#xa0;default9.  Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition frodefaultm elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance?default&#xa0;
defaultThe question is not so much about the regulation of the listed companies, but the regulation of the industries’ activities: the two are quite d
defaultifferent issues.  MPA cannot comment on the former, but can comment on the latter! 
default&#xa0;
default In this case it can be argued that the UK extractive minerals industries are already amongst the most heavily regulated industries in both the country and, probably, inte
defaultrnationally.  An MPA assessment in 2012 identified 228 laws and regulations related to planning and environmental matters requiring management by the mineral products industry.  There will be some items of legislation or regulation that seem misdirected or
default superfluous, but one thing is absolutely clear: the industry does not need any more regulation.  In terms of the UK being a centre of best practice on the world stage, there is no doubt that that is the case for the operations of the extraction processes 
defaultand all that goes therewith.  MPA cannot comment on whether this applies equally to corporate governance.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default10. What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre defaultfor them?default&#xa0;
defaultThe ownership of the UK extractive minerals industries has changed significantly over the past two decades.  20 years ago, ownership of the industries was almost exclusively in UK listed or private company hands.  However, within the MPA areas o
defaultf responsibility some 75% of extractive production, by volume and value, is now owned by international companies not based in the UK or listed in London.   The ownership of larger private and public SMEs operating in the UK is both UK and overseas based an
defaultd the 300 plus smaller SMEs operating in the UK are very largely private UK – owned businesses. 
